comments.content:
@Vladimir: your remark on the evolution of numerals is fascinating, I would love to read about it.

@riccard0: the averia is interesting, eerie and familiar. Thank you.

@eliason: there is plenty of luck to have here already! But I concur that the recognition of letterforms impose to ability to compare, and the 'knowledge' of templates, so I should investigate. In addition to a geometric analysis, I would also like to see reflexions on the nature of letter forms, semio/socio/psycho-logic aspects, poetic too, something like what Bachelard did for elements (space, fire, dreams) [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaston\_Bachelard](http://web.archive.org/web/20150322035045/http:/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaston_Bachelard "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaston\_Bachelard") and such a reflection, I think, should come from a combination of art and science. A conceptual foundation for typography that would feed into/explain the choices designers make daily in their choices: why egyptian slabs on the word 'God'? Why should the official printout of the european constitution have high ascenders?..etc.

@Nick: in what I have seen, most analysis of type is done of the "external" side of type. Let's define the "internal" side of type as the conceptual/abstract definition of letter forms, the "templates": e.g. an "o" is a circle, or vertical ellipse. The "external" aspect of type is about the surrounding aspects: counter size, ellipse direction, overhang dimension, natural/grunge aspects as you mention them,..etc. It's the internal aspects I'm interested about. I agree with you and the others that a geometric analysis of the external aspects doesn't lead far.

@DTY: very interesting, however I would ask an Artificial Intelligence team to go further: let's assume we have a group of A.I. beings, who are communicating orally with a basic language, then let's make them mute but let's give them the ability to draw.. what sort of shapes would they draw in order to communicate? In other words, what are the cognitive factors at play in the construction of a written language?

@Thomas: By template, I mean a visual template, a sort of abstract 2D wireframe, or a cloud made of the series of acceptable/recognisable shapes for a letter, so by 'template' I mean a geometric one so I'm not sure what you understood by templates not being geometric. And it's not necessarily about defining things with exact precision, but saying: a lowercase "c" is basically a left-side ellipse, has \_those\_ relations between the "i" and the "o", has \_these\_ characteristics compared to a "g".. and why does it need a terminal and/or a finial instead of being clear-cut at its center? For reasons of history or legibility? Is the "c" the easiest letter to write by hand, as it looks like it's part of a group of letters that don't need much ink/pixels? (hence: definition of letter "mass": does this exist?).. Amusing fact: the first word of the bible in yiddish is "Bereishit": בְּרֵאשִׁית which starts with a בְּ because, from what someone told me, it has an opening shape, like a uppercase "C"..  
As you can imagine, those questions or reflections are not related to particular (western) types, but to the abstract form of a letter, I'm just wandering who has written what about this kind of things.  
And I agree it's completely western-centric, as I have no familiarity with other alphabets. One does with what one has.  
But whatever the origin, an alphabet implies the ability to recognise a letter, visually (= geometrically), so the concept would still apply.

@Vladimir: thank you again, and it's a beautiful image that you've added. If you have sources for ignorant westerners to understand arabic scripts/alphabets, I'd be happy to look at them.

@rs\_donsata: I have a book, "the Art of Hand Lettering" by Helm Wotzkow, published in 1952, which is very humbling: imagine having to do draw by hand, and by hand only, perpetrating those school exercises every day in your professional life..

@Suijin: There are cognitive aspects to what I am looking for, and a reflection on letter shapes alone needs a complement of psychological studies (as you mentioned: pattern recognition, language development) if we were to make a proposition to alter our alphabet or language structure. Look at the example you gave: a study showing our capacity to understand words in which the orders of letters is randomised: it's an interesting study, but doesn't it feel that we're only at the beginning of something? Taking my personal interest and point of view: are there psychological studies on our capacity of recognition of specific abstract shapes, e.g. do we better recognise a series of circles, points, or segments? What are the pros and cons or using a stylised 'g' (a complex form) versus a simple one? Do we better recognise the 'g' (which I think is the most complex letter - geometrically speaking) or a 'o' or 'i'?  
Many aspects, related but distinct from typography as we usually see it.

@Nick: thank you again for those references. Being a software engineer myself, I'll read them a bit more, however they all are concerned with the exercise of rendering letters digitally, which I don't find very fascinating. Solutions based on restricted technology get always quickly outdated. I wonder for instance how the latest screen technologies (e.g. Apple Retina) changed the techniques of hinting or antialiasing, but it's not very exciting.

@Vladimir: yesssss for colored animated 3d types, and at first, dynamic intelligent ligatures, smart poly-angular italics, poly-size bold, colors that detect and adapt to background. I want to type "Here beginneth the story of..." and I want my text editor to draw me something like:  
 ![](http://web.archive.org/web/20150322035045im_/http:/40.media.tumblr.com/790ecb4f8ab2ea10342db89541e5fb51/tumblr_ngsvtnwgbH1u0q4t0o3_500.jpg)  
But we're digressing..  
Were you looking at [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arabic\_numerals](http://web.archive.org/web/20150322035045/http:/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arabic_numerals "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arabic\_numerals")?  
I find [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bakhshali\_manuscript](http://web.archive.org/web/20150322035045/http:/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bakhshali_manuscript "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bakhshali\_manuscript") particularly beautiful and inspiring:  
 ![](http://web.archive.org/web/20150322035045im_/http:/upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/64/Bakhshali_numerals_1.jpg/800px-Bakhshali_numerals_1.jpg)

@Nick: you may not think glyphs matter, I believe they do. I believe recognising a glyph, any glyph, into a letter, is only the tip of an iceberg. I'd like at least to convince you that each glyph has a poetic substance, is a fantastic source for childhood imagination, a monument to be celebrate. It shouldn't be hard, for a visual audience such as yours. So here are some random thoughts: Haven't you ever felt that the uppercase P or F were in danger of falling? Do you sense the majesty of the A, Eiffel tower, star of the alphabet. The B is so fat it's not even funny. One can't spell slim, thin, and lean with it. Glyphs have friends: p,q,d,b make a gang, x and o conspire in secret. Who will write the eternal beauty of an H, ladder to Heaven? Who will say there's simply something wrong and awkward with k, r and Q?  
More seriously, is our alphabet geometrically sound? In the sense of: is there a geometric balance between all letters or are some letters very different from each other while some are very (too) similar to each other? I am surprised by the purity of x and o and their opposition, and I wonder if the resemblance of m and n and u may be a (hidden, taboo) legibility issue. What shapes does our alphabet ignore? The tree letters c, u, n have open counters going right, up, down, but why not (suspending our anthropocentric judgement) a letter with a left one, like a b without a stem?  
(I'm not trying to be clear - just throwing a few thoughts to express why I care about those abstract shapes.)

@Vladimir: beautiful electronic spin font! Trying to read your paper...
